owl:Class.rdfs:label: a·πá·∏ças (domes)

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Curtains located behind the royal door of an iconostasis, separating the nave from the sanctuary. Some Eastern churches have only the curtains without the iconostasis. In Christian theological interpretation, the New Testament reference to the rending of the temple curtains at Jesus' death came to signify his passing through the heavenly boundary, thus the curtain was continued in certain liturgies.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: iconostasis curtains

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: The strong outer works of a fortification, usually low enough to permit defensive fire.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: bulwarks

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Shutters having louvers or slats positioned vertically in a frame rather than horizontally; distinct from "vertical blinds," which have vertical slats or panels, but are typically lighter-weight and attached at the top rather than in a frame.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: vertical shutters

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Interior shutters used to cover the bottom half a a window for privacy.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: caf√©-style shutters

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Sets of shutters are vertically mounted one above the other within the same opening, allowing each set to function independently.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: double-hung shutters

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Window or door shutters consisting of a number of horizontal slats hinged together and configured so they may be raised by rolling them onto a roller; operated by hand or motorized.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: roller shutters

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Window or door shutters having louvers, which are horizontal slats that are movable and may be angled to admit light and air, but to keep out rain and snow. The louvers are set into a frame to make a shutter.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: louvered shutters

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Window or door shutters having panels rather than louvers set into a frame.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: panel shutters

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Louvered shutters having deep louvers, over 2 inches wide; typically installed into the casement of a window.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: plantation shutters

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Window shutters having a vertical folding blade system in a frame, designed to cover a large expanse quickly. An example of such shutters is for hurricane protection. For window coverings with lighter weight vertical slats attached only at the top, use "vertical blinds."
owl:Class.rdfs:label: accordion shutters

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Shutters comprising vertical planks or boards held together by horizontal or diagonal battens.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: board-and-batten shutters

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Exterior shutters, usually louvered shutters or jalousies, characterized by being hinged at the top and opening from the window like an awning instead of horizontally. They are designed to provide protection from severe storms.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Bermuda shutters

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Shutters of various types, designed or used to provide protection for doors and windows from severe wind and weather.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: storm shutters

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Doors, usually unframed, formed of narrow vertical boards or planks held together by cross-pieces, battens, nailed to them. They may be constructed with two layers of planks, positioned on either side of the battens.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: batten doors

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Windows made of composite material such as fiberglass and resin compounds or chemically‚Äìbonded blends of wood and plastic resins.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: composite windows

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Altaar in een huiskapel of in een andere kamer van het huis. Ook wel aanduiding voor een tot een ensemble samengestelde groep devotionalia.
Altars in a domestic setting rather than a public space. Examples have existed since ancient times in many cultures and religions.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: house altars
huisaltaar
huisaltaren

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Tabernacles in Christian churches or chapels that hold the consecrated host and are built into the wall, usually near the main altar, rather than being free-standing.
Tabernakel, ingebouwd in een muur, afgesloten met een deur. Kan de grootte hebben van een kast.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: muurtabernakel
muurtabernakels
wall tabernacles

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Bekroning op de vier hoeken van een baldakijn - draagbaar of nagelvast - bijvoorbeeld struisvogelpluimen of andere ornamenten.
Crowns that appear at the four corners or surmounting the peaks of baldachins. These may be portable or permanently fixed, and may be ornamented in various ways, often with ostrich feathers.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: baldachin crowns
baldakijnbekroning
baldakijnbekroningen

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Sets of steps used to provide access to an altar; particularly as used with altars in a temple or church. They may be permanent steps or a portable set of steps. The uppermost step is often decorated. The number of steps varies, but for symbolic reasons is typically an uneven number, usually three, five, or seven, including the upper platform.
Verplaatsbaar trapje van enkele treden, waarop de priester kan staan bij de plaatsing in en het terugnemen uit de expositietroon op het tabernakel van de monstrans of de expositieciborie.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: altaartrap
altaartrappen
altar steps

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Curtains hung around the altar, particularly in a temple or church. They were hung in front of, or to close off the sides of, an altar during the service. As with rood screens, altar veils were liturgical barriers marking the boundaries between the congregation's space and the holy of holies; the Lenten veil is a type of altar veil, used in Catholic and other churches in the season prior to Easter. Beginning in the early days of the Reformation, altar vela began to be used in certain Protestant churches during the entire liturgical year. In some cases, altar veils may be associated with the "altar canopy."
Gordijn dat rond het altaar hangt.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: altaar vela
altaarvelum
altaarvelums
altar veils

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Distinctive chests, often portable, designed for the altar to be collapsible or otherwise fit into a chest, along with the other essential items required for the liturgy. The term may also apply to chests associated with a separate altar, whether or not they are portable or were intended to be hidden. Well-known examples of collapsible portable altar chests, intended to be hidden, were those used in northern Europe in the 17th-18th centuries, during times of prohibition of the celebration of Catholic Mass.

Draagbaar altaar met altaarsteen, uitgevoerd als een uitklapbare kist. In de kist zat een volledige uitrusting voor de eucharistieviering. Dit 'onzichtbare' altaar werd gebruikt in tijden van verbod op de viering van de katholieke eredienst in de zeventiende en achttiende eeuw, de schuilkerkperiode.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: altaarkist
altaarkisten
altar chests

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Cushioned steps or detached cushions for the step located in front of or around an altar, used at a Mass or other Christian service. An example of usage is by kneeling acolytes, deacons, and sub-deacons during solemn segments of the worship.
Kussen op de altaartrede waarop wordt geknield tijdens plechtige gedeelten van de eredienst. Bestemd voor misdienaars, diakens en subdiakens.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: altaarkussen
altaarkussens
altar kneelers

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: In Christian churches or places of other religious services, stands or tables used for the collection plate or other offertory gifts.
Standaard voor collecteschaal.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: collectestandaard
collectestandaarden
offertory tables

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Ceremoni√´le parasol met afwisselend rode en gouden banen (in de basilica maior) of rode en gele banen (in de basilica minor). Onderscheidingsteken voor een door de paus als zodanig benoemde basiliek. Staat aan de noordzijde van het altaar opgesteld in een standaard, steeds in combinatie met het tintinnabulum dat aan de zuidzijde van het altaar is opgesteld. Wordt ook soms umbrella genoemd.

General term for all ornamental canopy-like coverings of cloth, stone, wood, or metal used in a Christian church, such as to crown an altar, tabernacle, throne, pulpit, or statue. Examples are the structure covering an altar, formerly fitted with curtains and supported on four pillars; the covering suspended over the throne occupied by dignitaries of the Church or princes; the covering under which the Blessed Sacrament is sometimes borne in processions; or the parasol-like object sometimes placed on the north side of the altar in a stand.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: conopea
conopea (liturgical canopies)
conopeum

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Gemetseld bassin voor de doop door onderdompeling, zoals dat binnen sommige kerkgenootschappen gebeurt.
Sunken pools or above-ground tubs designed and used for Christian baptism by immersion. The earliest examples resemble Jewish mikveh pools.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: baptismal baths
doopbassin
doopbassins

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Altaarkast, waarin een draaibare inrichting, meestal verdeeld in twee of drie compartimenten. In √©√©n deel wordt het vaatwerk met de geconsacreerde hosties bewaard, een tweede deel kan als expositietroon worden gebruikt en het derde deel bevat een geschilderde of gebeeldhouwde voorstelling, bijvoorbeeld een gekruisigde Christus.

Tabernacles in Christian churches having multiple compartments or niches, usually two or three, each of which can be revealed or brought forward using a rotating device. The compartments typically could hold a monstrance, a ciborium, and a crucifix; the niches could be highly decorated. Rotating tabernacles were considered mechanical marvels, and were relatively rare, most common in 18th-century northern European Roman Catholic churches.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: draaitabernakel
draaitabernakels
rotating tabernacles

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Curtains of precious fabric suspended behind a figure as an act of veneration. The tradition had origins in honorific hangings behind the place where a ruler sat or stood. In pictorial convention, the depiction of similar hanging cloths was extended to appear behind sacred figures and portraits of all kinds, not just portraits of rulers. For similar fabrics arranged in a canopy, use "cloths of estate."

Kleed van kostbaar weefsel, dat werd opgehangen achter belangrijke beelden om de bijzondere status van de afgebeelde persoon te benadrukken. Tot in de zestiende eeuw werden ook wel erekleden aangebracht in brokaatschildering of geperst brokaat.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: cloths of honor
erekleden
erekleed

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Containers in Christian churches, made in the form of a dove and designed to be hung by chains over the altar. They had a door, sometimes hidden under a wing or on the back, that concealed a small cavity once used to hold the eucharistic bread. Eucharistic doves were formerly part of the standard liturgical furnishings for churches that could afford them. They were typically made of gold, silver, or another metal with enamelwork.

Van oorsprong middeleeuwse bewaarplaats voor geconsacreerde hosties. Deze holle duif heeft een opening met deksel in zijn rug. Hing aan kettingen aan het gewelf boven het altaar, verbeeldde de Heilige geest en de aanwezigheid van God. De duif kon omhoog getrokken worden, anders gezegd, vanuit de hemel (het gewelf van de kerk) nederdalen op het moment waarop de geconsacreerde hosties werden gebruikt. Zie ook: ciborie, lunuladoos, vasculum, pyxis, ziekenbusje, ziekendoosje.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: eucharistic doves
eucharistische duif
eucharistische duiven

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Altars that contain or are placed over a grave, sometimes of grand scale and serving as both a funerary altar and a commemorative monument. The form was highly developed in ancient Rome and was continued in the Christian era; particularly lavish examples date to the Baroque period. For tombs that mimic the form of an altar, but are not actually used as altars, use "altar tombs." To distinguish grave altars that held ashes rather than a corpse or other remains, use the more specific "cineraria (sepulchral monuments)."

Bij het grafaltaar wordt het altaarblad (mensa) gedragen door vier platen van hout of steen, die veelal in hoekzuilen samenkomen. De voorzijde kan worden geopend om bij het (relieken)graf te kunnen komen. Een grafaltaar functioneert daadwerkelijk als een graf.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: grafaltaar
grafaltaren
grave altars

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Tile architectural ornaments that anchor the end of a roof ridge.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: chiwei (edge ornaments)

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Tile architectural ornaments that anchor the ends of a roof ridges. A development of the chiwei form, the chiwen takes the form of a dragon head with the body of a fish. The mouth of the dragon appears to swallow the ridge, providing additional stability and support for the roof structure.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: chiwen

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: In churches, cloths and coverings used to conceal paintings, sculptures, and other items of luxury and beauty during the solemn Lenten season. For the curtains used to conceal the altar during Lent, use "Lenten veils."
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Lenten cloths

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Jewish ritual pools used for immersion during various purification procedures and rituals. The Jewish code of law prescribes the requirements for the quantity and nature of ritually appropriate water for ritual cleansing.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: mikvehs

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Special cloths placed over a Christian altar. Chrismales altar cloths are impregnated with wax to make them impermeable. They are placed directly on the brick or stone, under the other altar cloths, for the purpose of preventing chrism or other oils used in the consecration of the altar from seeping into the other, upper altar cloths.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: chrismales (altar cloths)

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Windows typically made of brick set in diverse openwork patterns, placed in walls for ornamental purposes.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: open-tracery windows

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Architectural elements found mounted on the walls of roofed walkways in gardens. Stone slates are typically inscribed with the calligraphy or drawings of well-known figures. An inscription recording the construction of the garden also occasionally appears on the slates.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: stone slates

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Roofs comprising beams that are covered with plant material, such as reeds or straw, in thick mats arranged and connected to the beams and battens in a way so that rain water is shed. In European tradition, an underlayer of plant material is permanent, and the upper weathering layer is replaced or repaired as needed over time. In tropical traditions, thatching may cover the roof as well as one or more walls.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: thatched roofs

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Transverse beams in Christian churches that span the nave at the entrance to the chancel or choir, and that separated the area around the altar from the area set aside for the laity. They are most common in the Middle Ages or early Renaissance Later, 'rood screens' developed between the beam and the floor. The rood beam may bear carved or painted portraits of the apostles, but most often is surmounted by a triumphal cross or crucifix. Rood lofts also later evolved above the rood beam.

Verbindingsbalk tussen de koorwanden op de scheiding tussen koor en schip of koor en dwarsbeuk. Op de balk zijn portretten van de apostelen aangebracht, gebeeldhouwd of geschilderd. Op de apostelbalk kan ook een triomfkruis (kruisbeeld) met flankerende beelden staan (Maria en Johannes, soms aangevuld met twee vrouwenbeelden die kerk en synagoge verbeelden).
owl:Class.rdfs:label: apostelbalk
apostelbalken
rood beams

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Houten stijl in en tegen een muur, meestal verbonden en een hecht geheel vormend met een balk, sleutelstuk en korbeel

Vertical architectural wall elements comprising wooden posts; used often, but not exclusively, in interior roof construction. For posts carried on corbels or other elements partway up the wall in open-timber roof trusses, use "pendant posts"; see also "crown posts." For solid supports of masonry or another material that extend the full height of the wall, and that are designed to sustain vertical pressure, use "piers (supporting elements)."
owl:Class.rdfs:label: muurstijl
muurstijlen
wall posts

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Altaar waarbij het altaarstuk boven de altaartafel is geflankeerd door twee of meerde zuilelementen en bekroond met een fronton (vanaf de late renaissance).

Monumental altars having a superstructure resembling a portico, originally including two or more pillars and a pediment, usually with a sculptural group or altarpiece. The Christian form developed from ancient altars, such as the Pantheon; it was most common in the Renaissance and Baroque periods.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: portico altars
portiekaltaar
portiekaltaren

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Coverings and curtains, usually black in color, placed over sculptures, paintings, mirrors, and other elements at an altar or elsewhere in a church, or in another public or private building; used to signify mourning, such as during a requiem service or during a mourning period. For similar coverings designed particularly for the Lenten season, prefer "Lenten veils." For banners used in procession or hung in funerary settings, use "mourning banners."
Speciale bekleding van altaaronderdelen of ander (kerkelijk) meubilair of (kerkelijke) architectuuronderdelen bij gelegenheid van begrafenis of rouwdienst.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: mourning cloths
rouwbekleding
rouwbekledingen

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Altaar waarbij onder de mensa een sarcofaag staat, al dan niet met relieken.

Altars for which the mensa rests on a sarcophagus containing relics. These developed from the Early Christian practice of celebrating the Eucharist slabs placed directly on the tombs saints. The creation of sarcophagus altars flourished in the 16th-17th centuries.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: sarcofaagaltaar
sarcofaagaltaren
sarcophagus altars

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Chairs designed for the use of the priest or other celebrant presiding at a Christian mass or other service. The chairs are usually of substantial size and having arms, placed in the choir of the church. For a set of three chairs or seats on a recessed bench for the celebrant, deacon, and sub-deacon, use "sedilia." For the chairs of a presiding bishop, use "cathedrae (bishop's chairs)." For chairs specifically for a presiding Protestant preacher, use "preacher's chairs."
in de Roomse- en Oud-Katholieke kerken: stoel met lage rugleuning in het priesterkoor, ter zijde van het altaar, waarop de priester plaats neemt bij de vespers.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: presider's chairs
vesperstoel
vesperstoelen

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Stoffen of papieren wandbekleding die op een fijn houten raamwerk, bespannen met jute of linnen en grondpapier, wordt aangebracht, waardoor direct contact met de wand wordt vermeden. Dit komt de duurzaamheid ten goede en er wordt een diepte-effect gecre√´erd

Wall coverings comprising fabric. In traditional wall-upholstering, fabric is attached to the wall by a series of clips, tacks, or tracks that hold the fabric tautly in place. Another method calls for the mounting of fabric on light frameworks of wood or another material, often fitted with an infill layer of batting. The latter method in particular is used to provide acoustical panels.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: bespanningen
upholstered walls
wandbespanning
wandbespanningen

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Cross-shaped fixtures or painted marks in Catholic churches, most often on the walls or columns at the places consecrated with chrism during the consecration of the church. The symbolism for the crosses is laid out in liturgical treatises, such as the "Rationale" of Durandus; there are twelve consecration crosses to symbolize the twelve apostles.

Kruisvormige markering in de kerk (meestal op de muren of op zuilen) van de plek waar de bisschop de kerk met chrisma wijdde. Behoort tot een serie van twaalf wijdingskruisen, die de twaalf apostelen symboliseren, daarom ook wel apostelkruisen werden genoemd.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: apostelkruis
apostelkruisen
consecration crosses
wijdingskruis
wijdingskruisen

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Altars in Christian churches that are under the same ecclesiastical canons as the high altar, but considered subordinate to the high altar. Side altars are typically placed at the head of a side aisle, along the sides of the aisle, or in a bay or chapel; they are often decorated with an altarpiece, wall paintings, windows, or other art referring to the titular saint to whom the altar is dedicated. Rules may state the allowable size, number of steps, or absence of a tabernacle for a side altar. Side altars were ranked in importance; the side altar on the Gospel side of the high altar had the highest status, and the counterpart on the Epistle side had the second highest rank. Side altars appeared in church architecture by the 6th century; they became prime places for members of the congregation to display their wealth and importance through patronage.
De twee nevenaltaren op de grens van koor en schip die het hoogaltaar flankeren worden de zijaltaren genoemd.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: side altars
zijaltaar
zijaltaren

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Hindu architectural elements in the form of faces or masks representing a monster with huge fangs, and gaping mouth, engaged in swallowing. Common in Indian and Southeast Asia.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: kƒ´rttimukhas

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Holes in the ground used to hold the foot of post components of fences or other structures. In the context of archaeology, these are recognizable as circular patches of darkened earth, where wood has decayed, or the hole has later been filled with a different material. Postholes are important to archaeologists to plot the layout of former building structures.

Kuil in de grond waarin een paal kon worden geplaatst. Herkenbaar als een ronde vlek waar de aarde verkleurd is, omdat het hout is vergaan of de kuil later is opgevuld met een ander materiaal. Paalgaten zijn belangrijk voor archeologen om het grondplan van vroegere bouwwerken te kunnen reconstrueren.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: paalgat
paalgaten
postholes

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Norman keeps, usually on the sites of older structures, and consisting of a stone wall on top of a motte, or steep mound. Within this wall, or shell, other buildings were contructed, using the wall as support, leaving an open courtyard in the center. A successor to the motte-and-bailey castle.

Opvolger van het mottekasteel waarbij de houten palissade vervangen wordt door een stenen muur bovenaan de motte. De slottoren werd tegen deze muur aangebouwd, zodat er een ronde binnenplaats ontstond.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: ringburcht
ringburchten
ringwalburcht
ringwalburchten
shell keeps

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Small portable altars, most often made of terracotta, but also of stone. These usually have a square or rectangular shape with varying dimensions. Arulae are considered too small to have been used for animal sacrifice, and are commonly decorated with moldings at top and bottom and with molded reliefs on one or more sides. Characteristic products of South Italy and Sicily from the the second quarter of the sixth century through the Roman period. They have been found in sanctuaries, near or inside graves, and in habitation sites.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: arulae

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Case furniture for storing altar frontals and other antependia, usually located in the sacristy of the church.
Kast voor het opbergen van de antependia.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: antependiumkast
antependiumkasten
frontal cupboards

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Frames for altar frontals (antependia), particularly frames that serve to suspend or hold textile antependia in place.
Losse, vaak versierde, vergulde of verzilverde lijst rondom een antependium.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: altar frontal frames
antependiumlijst
antependiumlijsten

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Kandelaar bij het wijdingskruis. De kaars brandt op het feest van kerkwijding.
Wall fixtures in the interior of a consecrated church, used for holding candles at the twelve consecration crosses arranged down the aisle the church.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: apostelkandelaar
apostelkandelaaren
consecration candlesticks

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Houder of arm waarin het doopbekken rust. Dikwijls aan de kuip of trap van de preekstoel bevestigd.

Supports of various design for the baptismal font, particularly for basin-style fonts. Examples include tabletop supports and metal supports mounted on a wall or other church architecture. For holders of baptismal fonts that rest on the floor, use "baptismal font stands."
owl:Class.rdfs:label: baptismal font supports
doopbekkenhouder
doopbekkenhouders

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Staander van hout of metaal, waarop het doopbekken rust.
Stands of various designs that rest on the floor or ground and support the baptismal font. For tabletop or wall-mounted supports for the baptismal font, use "baptismal font supports."
owl:Class.rdfs:label: baptismal font stands
doopbekkenstandaard
doopbekkenstandaarden

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Metalen boog - meestal van geelkoper - boven de doorgang in het doophek naar de dooptuin.

Spaces in a church marked by an arch, usually as the entrance to an apse or chapel, coinciding with the part of the building containing a font for the baptismal rite. The open space beneath the arch may be spanned by a gate, grillwork, or door.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: baptistery arches
doopbogen
doopboog

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Metalen of houten hek ter afsluiting van de dooptuin of doopkapel.

Screens separating the baptismal font and area from the rest of the church; may comprise a solid screen, open screen work, or a railing. For separate structures or chapels used for baptisms, use "baptistries."
owl:Class.rdfs:label: baptismal screens
doophek
doophekken

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Kerkbank voor de leden van het Hof. De identiteit van de hofleden kan worden afgeleid van het snijwerk en het familiewapen.
Pews in a church reserved for the royal family; the pews may be set up on a high platform or otherwise decorated and designated as belonging to the monarch or family.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: hofbank
hofbanken
royal pews

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Altars in Catholic churches installed after the Second Vatican Council (1962-1965) in accordance with new mandates that the altar should be table-like and placed far enough away from the wall so that the celebrant could face the congregation rather than have his back to them. Churches dating before the 1960s may retain the structures of the original high altars that are nearer the wall and having ornate superstructures, although they are no longer used for celebrating the mass. Altars from other periods and other faiths may be similar in design to council altars; the distinction is the context in which the council altar was installed.

Ter onderscheiding van het oude hoogaltaar tegen de oostwand van het koor, waaraan de priester met de rug naar het volk de mis opdroeg, wordt de term gebruikt voor het meer centraal geplaatste altaar waaraan de priester met het gezicht naar de kerkgangers de eucharistie met het volk viert.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: council altars (Roman Catholic church)
dienstaltaar
dienstaltaren

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Antependium in de liturgische kleur van de dag dat wordt geplaatst aan de voorzijde van de kaarsenbank.
Coverings of cloth or other material used to decorate or cover the gradine or altar ledge of the altar in Christian churches.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: gradine covers
kaarsenbankantependia
kaarsenbankantependium

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Stools or other types of simple seats in the choir of a church, used by acolytes or other assistants of the celebrant.
Zetels, soms opvouwbaar, bedoeld voor de misdienaren. De misdienaarskrukken maken soms ook deel uit van de set van kerkgestoelte.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: acolyte seats
misdienaarskruk
misdienaarskrukken

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Chairs of various designs, positioned at the front of certain Protestant churches and used by the preacher during services. For chairs having a tall back surmounted by a lectern and used as a pulpit, use "preaching chairs."

Zetel, veelal in de nabijheid van de liturgische tafel, waarop de predikant plaatsneemt tijdens momenten van rust in de dienst, zoals tijdens het zingen van een lied, tijdens de collectes en wanneer iemand anders dan de predikant een lezing verricht. Vaak wordt ook met een stoel genoegen genomen.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: preacher's chairs (presider's chairs)
predikantenzetel
predikantenzetels

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Niches having a shelf or flat surface, found in churches and used for the placement of vessels used in the Eucharist prior to use and immediately afterwards.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: credence niches

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Shelves found in churches and used for the placement of vessels used in the Eucharist prior to use and immediately afterwards.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: credence shelves

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: In architecture and engineering, the divisions, parts, extent, distances, or spaces between supporting elements; for example between the abutments of an arch, the supports of a beam, the piers of a bridge, or the walls carrying a roof or dome.

Verwijst in architectuur en techniek naar de afscheidingen, onderdelen, grootte, afstanden of ruimten tussen ondersteunende elementen, bijvoorbeeld tussen de steunpijlers van een boog, de ondersteuning van een balk, de pijlers van een brug of de muren die een dak of koepel dragen.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: overspanning
overspanning (structureel bouwelement)
overspanningen
overspanningen (structurele bouwelementen)
spans (structural elements)

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Arched roofs erected over platforms with a single pitch on each side of a central ridge.
Gewelfde daken boven platforms met √©√©n punt aan elke zijde van een centrale nok.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: parapludak
parapludaken
umbrella roofs

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: A set of orders of architecture, typically reserved for the five orders of architecture known in ancient Greece and Rome, usually including Ionic, Doric, Corinthian, Composite, and Tuscan.

Term die verwijst naar een verzameling architectuurordes, meestal gereserveerd voor de vijf architectuurordes in het oude Griekenland en Rome, namelijk Ionisch, Dorisch, Korinthisch, Composiet en Toscaans.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: classical orders
klassieke orde
klassieke ordes

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Fa√ßades and other exterior walls having an overall design, such as stripes or geometric patterns, comprising stones of contrasting colors. Examples are the distinctive polychrome fa√ßades that typify Tuscan architecture.

Fa√ßades en andere buitenmuren met een algemeen ontwerp, bijvoorbeeld strepen of geometrische patronen, dat gemaakt is van stenen in contrasterende kleuren. Voorbeelden zijn de polychrome fa√ßades die kenmerkend zijn voor de Toscaanse architectuur.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: polychrome fa√ßade
polychrome fa√ßades
polychrome fa√ßades

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Architectural order characterized especially by the use of rusticated columns and introduced by the French architect Delorme
Architectuurorde die met name wordt gekenmerkt door het gebruik van in rustiek werk uitgevoerde kolommen. De orde is ge√Øntroduceerd door de Franse architect Delorme.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Franse orde
French order

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Architectural order similar to the Ionic order, but differing in that the capital features a palmette motif rising between the two outer volutes, rather than being linked horizontally by a form at the top of the capital.
Architectuurorde die lijkt op de Ionische order, maar afwijkt doordat het kapiteel een palmetmotief heeft tussen de twee buitenste voluten, en niet horizontaal aan de bovenkant verbonden is.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Aeolic order
Aeolische orde

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Rails of panelen die van de lateibalk tot de drempel van de deur lopen en daarmee de deurlijst in twee delen splitsen.
Rails or panels stretching from the lintel to the sill of doors, dividing the doorframe into two parts.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: replumi
replumi

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Walkways, typically behind the parapets, along the tops of defensive fortications such as those found in castles or as part of city walls.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: vamures (wall components)

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Atars in the form of a table.
Hoge monumentale tafel die als altaar in gebruik is.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: altaartafel
altaartafels
altar tables
mensa's

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Een muur of schutting die in een tuin of fruitboomgaard werd geplaatst om de fruitbomen te beschermen tegen weer en wind. De muren werden naar het zuiden en zuidoosten gericht waarbij de fruitbomen aan de zuidzijde van de muren werden geplaatst. Zo stonden ze optimaal in de zon, de nissen zorgen voor een microklimaat met weinig wind en de stenen geven nadat de zon weg is lange tijd warmte af.

Walls or fences that are placed in a garden or orchard to protect fruit trees from wind and weather. Of varied design, they generally provide a microclimate that preserves warmth after the sun has set.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: fruit walls
fruitmuren
fruitmuur

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Freestanding exterior walls that curve back and forth regularly along their length. Typically made of brick, the zig-zag or serpentine configuration does not have buttresses, thus differing from the superficially similar "garland wall"; the strength of the serpentine walls derives from the wavy configuration, allowing them to be only one brick thick. This Dutch form was introduced in Britain in the 17th cedntury when Dutch engineers drained the fen country; it was taken up elsewhere in Europe and North America. Often used to enclose gardens.

Fruitmuren van een halve steen dik op doorgaande golvende of slingerende plattegrond, bestaande uit regelmatig elkaar afwisselende cirkelsegmenten. Te onderscheiden van 'slingermuren', die muurdelen tussen pijlers heeft.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: serpentine walls
slangenmuren
slangenmuur

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Tot op de vloer doorlopend, naar binnen draaiend raam bestaande uit twee vleugels. Aan de buitenkant is gewoonlijk een ijzeren hek aangebracht, een zogenaamd 'Frans balkon'.

Windows that extend to the ground or nearly to the ground. For floor-length wall openings consisting entirely or mostly of glass panels and hinged on one side so they may function as either doors or windows, use "French doors" if they are single doors or "French windows" if they are a pair of units.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: fen√™tre √† terre
fen√™tres √† terre
fen√™tres √† terre

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Gables having an underlying triangular or rectangle form with curved sides; so-named because they resemble the cross-section of a bell or a 17th-century mantle clock. If the gable is surmounted by a pediment, it is often called a "Dutch gable."
Gevels waarvan de top de vorm heeft van een klok.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: bell gables (wall components)
klokgevel
klokgevels

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Venstertype dat bestaat uit twee boven elkaar geplaatste ramen van ongeveer gelijke grootte, waarbij het onderste raam doorgaans afsluitbaar is met een luik. Het bovenste gedeelte van het venster laat continu licht door.
Window having a long rectangular shape and comprising a two-light frame, with a shutered lower half topped by a glazed half.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: kloosterkozijn
kloosterkozijnen
kloosterkozijns
kloostervenster
kloostervensters

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Blinden die zijdelings kunnen worden opgevouwen.
Window shutters that can be folded sideways with hinged articulations.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: folding shutters
vouwblind
vouwblinden

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Protruding angles of bastions or other fortifications, where the faces (i.e. the angle sides directed towards the attacker) converge.
Uitspringende punten van bastions of andere verdedigingswerken, daar waar de faces (i.e. de naar de aanvaller gerichte zijden van een hoek) samenkomen.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: saillant
saillanten
salients

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Covering masses like ramparts made of fascines and earth, raised to protect soldiers from the fire of the enemy. In more formal fortifications, this may refer to the corner angle of a bastion.
Vleugelvormige uitbouw, aangebracht aan de zijkant(en) van een bastion.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: epaulement
epaulementen
epaulements

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Artificial mounds used as a lower rampart, located in front of the main rampart of a fortification.
Wordt gebruikt voor een lage wal gelegen voor de hoofdwal van een vesting en bedoeld voor de nabijheidsverdediging van een vesting
owl:Class.rdfs:label: faussebraye
faussebrayes
faussebrayes
onderwal
onderwallen
voorwal
voorwallen

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Een ingesprongen artillerie batterij, of verschansing √† Cr√©maill√®re, gebouwd als een zaagtand met uitspringende en herintredende hoek voor het verkrijgen van een schuine, evenals een directe beschieting en bescherming tegen enfileervuur van de vijand.
Fortifications constructed with salient and re-entering angles for obtaining an oblique, as well as a direct fire, and to afford shelter from an enfilade fire of the enemy.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: cr√©maill√®re
cr√©maill√®res
indented batteries

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Sluices for flooding low farm lands, for defense purposes.
Sluis voor het onder water zetten van lage landbouwgronden, als middel tot verdediging.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: inundatiesluis
inundatiesluizen
inundation sluices

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Covers or shutters fitted in grooves to slide open and closed over a relatively small window or similar opening, such as on a ship or wall.
Zijwaarts of opwaarts te schuiven schotten of panelen, waarmee openingen, vooral vensters, kunnen worden afgesloten.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: schuifblind
schuifblinden
schuifluik
schuifluiken
sliding hatches
vensterluik
vensterluiken

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Gables having a triangular form with a rectangular protrusion at the apex; so-named because the form resembles a cross-section of an inverted funnel or spout.
Gevels waarvan de top eindigt in een smalle rechthoekige hals, gelijkend op een 'tuit'.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: spout gables
tuitgevel
tuitgevels

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Een kegeldak is een dakvorm in de vorm van een kegel met mogelijkheden van een stompe tot een spitse hoek.
Roofs that are circular in plan and that rise to terminate in a point, the whole forming a regular cone in shape.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: conical roofs
kegeldak
kegeldaken

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Dammen in de richting van de lopen van rivieren, hetzij ter beveiliging van holle oevers of van brugpijlers, hetzij tot beperking van de rivier tot de normale breedte.
Dams oriented in the direction of the flow of a river, as protection for hollow river banks or of bridge piers, or for limiting the river's normal width.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: blinde dam
blinde dammen
off-bankline revetments
strekdam
strekdammen

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Gedeelte van een bastion dat grenst aan de courtine.
Parts of bastions that connect the curtain to the face and that are in defense of the opposite face, and the passage of the ditch.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: flank
flanken
flanken (bastiononderdelen)
flanks (bastion components)

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Kleinere deuren in grote deuren of poorten, alsook in een sluisdeur.
Smaller doors within larger doors or gates, designed to allow passage without opening the larger door.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: inloopdeur
inloopdeuren
klinket
klinketten
wicket doors
winket
winketten

coupures

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Een klein vestingwerk, bestaande uit twee verdedigingswallen (facen genaamd), die elkaar onder een hoek raken. Het zo ontstane werk kan zelfstandig zijn (in de vorm van een versimpelde lunet, maar het is vaak onderdeel van een liniewal. De fl√®che is vrijwel identiek aan een redan, maar in dit geval raken de facen elkaar onder een hoek die scherper is dan 90 graden, terwijl bij een redan de hoek 90 graden exact is.

Part of the outworks of a fortress, built in front of the glacis, consisting of two converging faces forming a salient angle, forming an arrowhead shape.Similar to a redan, but with faces forming an acute angle.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: fl√®che
fl√®ches
fl√®ches (fortification elements)

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Gables having a triangular profile that is broken, usually at only one point on each side, with a step-shape.
Gevels waarvan de schuine kanten door een of twee horizontale platen, genaamd 'schouders' worden onderbroken.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: schoudergevel
schoudergevels
shoulder gables

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Massive and squat semi-circular towers in fortifications, precursors of "bastions."
Versterkt halfrond bolwerk van de vestingwal, oorspronkelijk waltorens, van waaruit flankerend vuur kon worden gegeven. Voorloper van het bastion.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: rondeel
rondelen

Systems of bars laid at road level designed to prevent cattle and game from entering or leaving a designated area, while allowing the passage of other traffic.

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Geulen in de lengterichting van 'natte grachten', ter vergroting van de hinderniswaarde; ook wel ijsvrij gehouden geulen in grachten.
Secondary trenches in the bottom of a moat or ditch, serving as a drain, and as an extra obstacle to possible attackers or to keep the ditch ice-free.

cunetten
cunettes

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Freestanding exterior walls, generally of brick, having buttresses joined by curved walls, forming a scallop-shaped footprint.
Fruitmuren, bestaande uit een doorgaande lijnvan gemetselde pijlers, waartussen gebogen halfsteens muren op de plattegrond van een cirkelsegment. Te onderscheiden van 'slangenmuren'.

slingermuren
slingermuur

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Meestal betonnen muren van zodanige hoogte en zwaarte dat deze niet door tanks kunnen worden overschreden of doorbroken; ook wel anti-tankmuren genoemd.
Walls, usually of concrete, built as fortifications specifically to prevent the progress of armored combat vehicles.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: anti-tank walls
anti-tankmuren
tankmuren
tankmuur

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Circular expansions at the corners of bastions, used to cover artillery deployed on the flank of the bastion from enemy fire.
Ronde uitbouwen aan schouderhoeken van bastions, dienende om op de bastionsflank opgeteld geschut tegen vijandelijk vuur te dekken.

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Meestal rond obstakel geplaatst op een dam in de vestinggracht om te voorkomen dat deze dammen worden gebruikt als middel om de gracht over te steken.
Tower-like structures placed atop dams or fortification walls to block passage across the wall or dam.

Triangular outworks situated in the moats of fortifications, and that resemble bastions with a crescent-shaped gorge, constructed to protect a bastion or curtain. The term is often used interchangeably with 'ravelins'. Historically there may have been distinguishing characteristics between ravelins and demi-lunes in the Italian school of fortification design, but in the modern era these terms are most often used synonymously.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: demi-lunes (outworks)

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: 'Batterijen' die een deel van een vestingwerk of tussengelegen terreinstrook flankeren; ook wel batterijen geplaatst op de flanken van vestingwerken.
Batteries flanking a part of a fortification.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: flank batteries
flankbatterij
flankbatterijen

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Dams built into walls across the ditches of a fortification, with a sluice gate than can regulate the height of water in the ditch at will.
Waterkeringen in een gracht als onderdeel van verdedigingswerken, om het water daarin op de stuwen en op een bepaalde plaats hoog te houden.

gevelstenen

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Goudleer, ook wel Cordoba-leer of Cuir de Cordoue, is een wanddecoratie van fijn leer (meestal van gelooide kalfshuiden), waarop afbeeldingen van bladzilver werden bevestigd, afgedekt met een goudkleurige vernis. Goudleerbehang diende tot het behangen van vertrekken in plaats van wandtapijten.
Interior wall decorations created from specially tooled, varnished, and colored panels of gilt leather.

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Stucco ceilings consist of a layer of plaster or other mortar arranged on a ceiling or vault as a decorative whole.

Stucplafonds (ook stucwerkplafonds) bestaan uit een laag pleister (of een andere mortel), die op een plafond of gewelf is aangebracht en daarna, al dan niet met behulp van sjablonen, op een kunstzinnige manier is bewerkt tot een decoratief geheel.

stucplafond

stucwerkplafond

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Gladde vloerbedekking opgebouwd uit lagen met bitumen ge√Ømpregneerd houtviltpapier, voorzien van een decoratief bedrukte slijtvaste bovenlaag. Balatum dat in rollen verkocht werd kende zijn grootste populariteit in het midden van de vorige eeuw toen het een goedkoop en makkelijker aan te brengen alternatief vormde voor linoleum en voor de opkomst van o.a. kamerbreed tapijt, vinylvloerbedekking en laminaatparket.

Waterproof floor covering material composed of layers of bitumen-impregnated felt cardboard, and provided with a printed decorative wear-resistant top layer. Sold in rolls, balatum had its greatest popularity in the middle of the 20th century as an alternative to true linoleum, as it was inexpensive and easy to apply. It was eventually replaced by vinyl products. Originally a brand name, it was manufactured beginning in 1924 at the Papeteries de Genval. The term often appears uncapitalized as a common noun to refer to any linoleum-like floor covering.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Balatum
balatum

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Wooden bracket set that is a main component of the traditional Chinese post-and-beam structure, along with the roof structure and the column grid. The origins of the Chinese bracketing system was a spreading block (dou) placed upon a column to support the beam above more broadly, and in depictions of curved arms (gong) attached near the top of the columns, parallel to the building wall, extending outward and up to help support the beam. In time, the block and arms were combined to create traditional Chinese brackets.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: dougong

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Small windows or other openings, sometimes closed by grilles, forming places of communication; typically placed in another window or opening. Examples are windows in banks for cashiers or tellers.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: wicket windows

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Pairs of tall casement windows closing against each other with no frame between them, allowing access to the outside or to another room. For single tall window-like doors, use "French doors."
owl:Class.rdfs:label: French windows

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Double windows of Dutch origin; windows are divided in four sections, with the lower halves covered by shutters or doors and the upper halves glazed. A related design is seen in "kloosterkozijns," resembling one-half of the kruiskozijn.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: kruiskozijns

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Gables having a triangular form, like a pediment; the term is often used to distinguish the simpler triangular form from more complex gable forms.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: triangular gables

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Gables having an overall tall, rectangular form; may be capped with a broken pediment or other form.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: neck gables

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Covers or doors, often half-doors or gates, that close relatively small windows or doors, which are also called "hatches (openings)."
owl:Class.rdfs:label: hatches (opening covers)

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: In certain large mosques, raised platforms where the m√ºezzin, the assistant of the imam, repeats the call to prayer at the start of each service, reads from the Koran, kneels to respond to the imam's prayers, etc.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: m√ºezzin mahfilis

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Arcades or porticoes in Islamic architecture. Riwaqs serve as transitions between interior and exterior spaces.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: riwaqs

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Windows made with stained glass.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: stained-glass windows

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Restraining structures incorporating a barrier that is raised or pushed aside at the start of a race, to ensure a simultaneous start for all competitors or to ensure consistent timing of each competitor. Examples are used in horse racing, foot races, downhill skiing, and other sports.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: starting gates

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Draaibare klep voor het afsluiten van de ovenmond.
Hinged doors¬†that cover the mouths of ovens.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: oven doors
ovendeur
ovendeuren

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: In traditional Chinese timber-frame architecture, refers to two eaves pillars framing the central bay on the sides of the building parallel to the roof ridge (typically the front side). Leveling pillars are used as a standard height for calculating the height of other pillars across the fa√ßade, as they increase in height from the center towards the corners of the building, allowing for an upward curvature of the eaves (shengqi). The term appears in the Yingzao Fashi (1103, Siku quanshu edition., 5.4b) and also in documents written by officials during the Song Dynasty (960-1279) to describe the architecture of mausolea. Modern architectural historians use this term to describe central-bay pillars on all sides of a building dating from the Tang (618-907) to early Ming (1368-1644) dynasties.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: pingzhu

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Walls having the primary purpose of serving to that separate, keep apart, demarcate, or serve as deterrents.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: barrier walls

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Fa√ßades that comprise a pavilion, usually an entryway.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: fa√ßade pavilions

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: A type of wood ceiling primarily found in Islamic, Spanish, or Moorish architecture. The structure is a series of girders with perpendicular beams, which are often carved, painted, or otherwise stylized. This type of ceiling, with variations, appears in Spanish colonial sites in the Americas as well as in Europe and North Africa.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: alfarje

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Carpets made using knots, in the most common method of creating pile carpets; knots are formed by tying yarn around two warp strands to form a knot on the surface of the textile. After each row of knots is created, one or more strands of weft are passed through the warp strands. Then the knots and the weft strands are beaten with a comb securing the knots in place. The number of knots per square inch determines the appearance and texture of the rug.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: knotted-pile carpets

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Capitals of the architectural style associated with the fifth of the traditional five classical orders of architecture, that also include Doric, Ionic, Corinthian, and Tuscan. It is characterized by the merging of Ionic and Corinthian stylistic elements in the capital, where the Ionic volute and the Corinthian acanthus leaves are combined to create a more lavish whole.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Composite capitals

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Capitals characteristic of the Classical Ionic style, having volutes as a prominent feature; the style is also characterized by richly carved moldings and columns with bases.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Ionic capitals

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Capitals of the Classical architectural Doric order, which is characterized by columns generally without bases, relatively simple capitals, and a frieze composed of alternating triglyphs and metopes.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Doric capitals

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Unadorned cushion capitals, characteristic of the Tuscan order.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Tuscan capitals

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Fireplace components formed of frameworks of metal bars, intended as supports for flammable materials, used in place of, or with, andirons.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: fireplace grates

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Type of siding made from vinyl, often replicating the visual qualities of other materials such as stone or wood.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: vinyl siding

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Sets, which are assemblages of scenery, props, and lighting and sound systems, that are designed or used for films.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: film sets

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Long timber threshhold for a pƒÅtaka storehouse. By observing the carved ornamentation and decoration on a pataka threshhold, visitors to a tribe would be able to ascertain the chief‚Äôs capacity to provide for his people and, therefore, the tribe‚Äôs capacity and strength to protect and fend for itself.

owl:Class.rdfs:label: acerras (altars)
